{"id":"1812.08345","submitter":"Alexander Garver","authors":"Alexander Garver, Rebecca Patrias, Hugh Thomas","title":"Minuscule reverse plane partitions via quiver representations","comments":"Comments welcome","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.RT math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A nilpotent endomorphism of a quiver representation induces a linear\ntransformation on the vector space at each vertex. Generically among all\nnilpotent endomorphisms, there is a well-defined Jordan form for these linear\ntransformations, which is an interesting new invariant of a quiver\nrepresentation. If $Q$ is a Dynkin quiver and $m$ is a minuscule vertex, we\nshow that representations consisting of direct sums of indecomposable\nrepresentations all including $m$ in their support, the category of which we\ndenote by $\\mathcal{C}_{Q,m}$, are determined up to isomorphism by this\ninvariant. We use this invariant to define a bijection from isomorphism classes\nof representations in $\\mathcal{C}_{Q,m}$ to reverse plane partitions whose\nshape is the minuscule poset corresponding to $Q$ and $m$. By relating the\npiecewise-linear promotion action on reverse plane partitions to\nAuslander-Reiten translation in the derived category, we give a uniform proof\nthat the order of promotion equals the Coxeter number. In type $A_n$, we show\nthat special cases of our bijection include the Robinson-Schensted-Knuth and\nHillman-Grassl correspondences.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 20 Dec 2018 03:14:45 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 4 Mar 2019 14:52:12 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 13 Dec 2022 23:13:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-15"}
{"id":"1812.08346","submitter":"Rahim Moosa","authors":"Jason Bell, Rahim Moosa, Adam Topaz","title":"Invariant hypersurfaces","comments":"Final version following minor changes suggested by the referee","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1017/S1474748020000262","report-no":null,"categories":"math.AG math.LO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The following theorem, which includes as very special cases results of\nJouanolou and Hrushovski on algebraic $D$-varieties on the one hand, and of\nCantat on rational dynamics on the other, is established: Working over a field\nof characteristic zero, suppose $\\phi_1,\\phi_2: Z \\to X$ are dominant rational\nmaps from a (possibly nonreduced) irreducible scheme $Z$ of finite-type to an\nalgebraic variety $X$, with the property that there are infinitely many\nhypersurfaces on $X$ whose scheme-theoretic inverse images under $\\phi_1$ and\n$\\phi_2$ agree. Then there is a nonconstant rational function $g$ on $X$ such\nthat $g\\phi_1=g\\phi_2$. In the case when $Z$ is also reduced the\nscheme-theoretic inverse image can be replaced by the proper transform. A\npartial result is obtained in positive characteristic. Applications include an\nextension of the Jouanolou-Hrushovski theorem to generalised algebraic\n$\\mathcal D$-varieties and of Cantat's theorem to self-correspondences.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 20 Dec 2018 03:23:17 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 5 Jun 2020 16:00:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-19"}
